      "date": "2024-03-11 09:33:29.000000000",
      "message": "Patch Set 1:\n\n> this patch addresses the regression on Ubuntu.\n\nHow does Debian now behave with this patch applied?",
      "accounts_in_message": [],
      "_revision_number": 1
    },
    {
      "id": "92d2540bbfe66653681f83b5909b251f6160f8ce",
      "author": {
        "_account_id": 888,
        "name": "Thomas Stibor",
        "email": "thomas@stibor.net",
        "username": "t.stibor@gsi.de"
      },
      "date": "2024-03-11 09:33:39.000000000",
      "message": "Patch Set 1: Code-Review+1\n\nI just tested the PR on Debian GNU/Linux 10 (buster).\nIt works without problems. When installing the DEB package the compiled Kernel\nmodules are copied to: /lib/modules/4.19.0-26-amd64/updates/kernel.\n\nI added the lines in a long time ago PR:\n\n'''DEPMOD_DIR=\"/etc/depmod.d\"\n\t\t\nLUSTRE_DEPMOD_FILE=\"${DEPMOD_DIR}/lustre.conf\"\n\t\t\n\t\t\n[ ! -d ${DEPMOD_DIR} ] && { mkdir -p ${DEPMOD_DIR}; }\n\t\t\n[ ! -e ${LUSTRE_DEPMOD_FILE} ] && { echo \"search updates/kernel built-in\" > ${LUSTRE_DEPMOD_FILE}; }'''\n\nbecause at that time (< 4.19) Lustre was in the official Kernel/Staging.The command '''modprobe lustre''' loaded the kernel/staging modules rather than the compiled from whamclould git. Since\nLustre is not in the official Kernel/Staging. The search order \"updates/kernel built-in\" can thus be removed.",
      "accounts_in_message": [],
      "_revision_number": 1
    },
